    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>67 Regent St Cambridge Thursdy 6 o'clock</p>
      <p>Dearest W. I have got a tiny Sitting &amp; Bed-room in a lodging house close bye here. It was impossible for the C--'s to take me in to sleep; but I am entirely with them of course in the day. I am very glad to have a day or two here; for I may not perhaps see them</p>
      <p>again very soon. They are only waiting for Charlotte's being able to move with safety, to go to the curacy fixed on. And by the bye I must not tell you about this. Sir George Craufurd, the Rector of Burgh, Spilsby, Lincolnshire, has known Calliphronas many years, &amp; is particularly partial to him. He has been, (I knew this spring), very desirous to</p>
      <p>get Calliphronas for his curate; &amp; offers him 100 a year; a wing of an excellent &amp; beautiful house he has been building at Burgh; the use of his carriage; &amp; various other advantages.</p>
      <p>He wrote very kind letters to both Hester &amp; Charlotte separately on the subject; &amp; seems to be very anxious to make them happy &amp; comfortable, &amp; indeed to give them every luxury almost.</p>
      <p>Sir G. Craufurd was</p>
      <p>I believe in India some years; I suppose also there in the clerical capacity. He came to the title &amp; property unexpectedly, in consequence of the death of his elder brother.</p>
      <p>N. B, he is a bachelor, between 40 &amp; 50. Hopes for H-- I think.</p>
      <p>I cannot help fancying that he must be related to your friend Craufurd. For the spelling of the name is a very unusual one. Of course no one can tell how all the parties</p>
      <p>will pull together until the arrangement has been actually tried. But it seems promising.</p>
      <p>I hear the locality is very healthy; the country hilly &amp; picturesque.</p>
      <p>Burgh is 4 miles from the coast. It is not at all in the fenny part of Lincolnshire. The Bishop of Lincoln has promised to ordain Calliphronas. He is a great friend of Sir G's.</p>
      <p>The ordination is to be on the 25th of Sepr. But</p>
      <p>they are to be established immediately; altho' of course Calliphronas cannot act officially yet.</p>
      <p>I find Charlotte in a very miserable state. They talk of moving next week; indeed on Monday. I cannot believe it possible however myself.</p>
      <p>I hope you have had as much rain as we have here today; &amp; which has been my plague &amp; torment. By the</p>
      <p>way you cannot think how I feel the inconvenience of my extreme delicacy as to damp &amp; temperature; &amp; which is certainly much beyond that of people of my years in general. I am obliged to take very great care. Indeed it is absolutely necessary; tho' no one hates coddling so much as I do. But medical people tell me that I must positively avoid all exposure &amp; chills. By this I don't mean</p>
      <p>that I am not to go out in any but very fine weather; but that both as to clothing, fires when there is the slightest damp or coolness, &amp; all means of protection from outward changes, I must be scrupulously careful.</p>
      <p>My mother is quite annoyed I think at perceiving my delicacy as to these matters; which is greater than that of Elizabeth even I fancy. The way that I am</p>
      <p>struck with shivering &amp; debility from any exposure is sometimes almost incredible. And yet I am very well &amp; strong at present, on the whole.</p>
      <p>Gamlen is gone over to Brampton today, for a night. I am delighted at this; tho' I lose him here; for he does not return to Cambridge.</p>
      <p>He holds me out hopes of a visit of a week to Ockham, this summer</p>
      <p>or autumn. This would be to me charming; &amp; hardly less so to you.</p>
      <p>Your sisters were quite amused &amp; pleased with his delight at so unexpectedly meeting me here yesterday. He took the bird in his arms, &amp; kissed her; &amp; then turning to them, said, "You know she is quite "my own little girl; &amp; as "such I must always "treat her. But believe "me, too I respect her as</p>
      <p>"much as I love her."</p>
      <p>He seems much attached now to both your Sisters; &amp; intends to have intercourse between Bossall &amp; Burgh. They tell me that his excellence &amp; rare superiority become more &amp; more manifest with every day's continued acquaintance.</p>
      <p>Dear me! If I could, what a nice colony of friends I would have to live with me! I would</p>
      <p>have F. Knight, Dr Locock, Gamlen, &amp; I think Kay Shuttleworth. And perhaps admit you as 5th; tho' really of what use an Old Crow could be to me I know not.</p>
      <p>You see the Bird is saucy today!--</p>
      <p>But yet she's a good bird too, is she not, to write you such long letters.</p>
      <p>What can the enclosed mean? Have you asked Fonblanque to Ockham, or what?</p>
    </div></body>
